[
    {
        "content": "<p>Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F:C\\to D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span> and suppose <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>:</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msup><mi>C</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><msup><mi>D</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></msup><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>S</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(F):[C^{op},Set]\\to [D^{op},Set]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is an equivalence. Then what do we know about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 237908793,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Williams",
        "timestamp": 1620433301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>motivating example: suppose <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is cartesian, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><msup><mi>C</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F:C\\to C^\\ast</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.688696em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.688696em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> freely adds exponentials. it seems like <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(F)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> might be an equivalence; but I'm not sure that's possible.</p>",
        "id": 237908877,
        "sender_full_name": "Christian Williams",
        "timestamp": 1620433375
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nope, F extends to an equivalence between the idempotent completions of C and D.<br>\nWhile Yoneda factors through <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>C</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.688696em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.688696em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is your motivating example, presheaves on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>C</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C^*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.688696em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.688696em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> are much bigger than presheaves on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 237937594,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1620461984
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>wait even what I said about Yoneda factoring through isn't accurate; if your F was the exponential <em>completion</em> of C (only adding ones which don't already exist) then Yoneda would factor through it. In any case, the same conclusion applies unless C is already cartesian closed.</p>",
        "id": 237937684,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1620462071
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Cool question. I think that if P(F) is an equivalence then F should be i.e. P reflects equivalences....this is my guess because I am pretty sure P is a 2-dimensional version of faithful.</p>",
        "id": 237961785,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1620485973
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are famous examples where P(F) is an equivalence even when F is not.</p>",
        "id": 237962548,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620486647
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example, there's a category C with one object such that presheaves on it are reflexive graphs, and C is a subcategory of the usual category D with <em>two</em> objects such that presheaves on it are reflexive graphs.</p>",
        "id": 237962686,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620486762
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think in this example i: C <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> D is fully faithful but not essentially surjective, so not an equivalence, yet P(i) is an equivalence.</p>",
        "id": 237962744,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620486836
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The point here is that D is the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Cauchy+complete+category#in_terms_of_splitting_of_idempotents\">Cauchy completion</a> of C - see the definition and also Theorem 2.2 at the link.</p>",
        "id": 237962933,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620486969
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Morgan's reply is a bit terse and cryptic:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Nope, F extends to an equivalence between the idempotent completions of C and D.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 237963012,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487081
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think he's trying to say: if F: C <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> D induces an equivalence of presheaf categories, F extends to an equivalence between the idempotent completions of C and D.</p>",
        "id": 237963118,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487158
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(It's always nice to spell out details of what one is trying to say here, even if it takes a bit of extra time.)</p>",
        "id": 237963203,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487224
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The idempotent completion is the same thing as the Cauchy completion.</p>",
        "id": 237963230,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487243
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And this fact:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If F: C → D induces an equivalence of presheaf categories, F extends to an equivalence between the Cauchy completions of C and D.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 237963256,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487272
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>is easy to prove using the nLab's definition of Cauchy completion.  I think.</p>",
        "id": 237963277,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487300
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Heuristically, the Cauchy completion on C proceeds by <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/split+idempotent\">splitting all idempotents</a> in C.  But the nLab describes the easy way to do this: form the category of presheaves on C, and then take the subcategory consisting of all <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/retract#definition\">retracts</a> of representables.</p>",
        "id": 237963484,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487510
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think if F : C <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> D induces an equivalence of presheaf categories P(F) : P(C) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> P(D), you can see P(F) restricts to an equivalence between the <em>subcategories</em> of the presheaf categories consisting of retracts of representables.</p>",
        "id": 237963627,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487658
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But this is just a way of saying F extends to an equivalence between the Cauchy completion of C and the Cauchy completion of D!</p>",
        "id": 237963706,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487718
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I say \"I think if\", because I haven't carefully checked.</p>",
        "id": 237963714,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487730
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The main point is that the retracts of representables have an invariant (i.e. depending only on the presheaf category) description as the objects <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> for which <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>−</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hom}(A, -)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> preserves all colimits.</p>",
        "id": 237963866,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1620487845
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks!</p>",
        "id": 237963901,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487872
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's great.</p>",
        "id": 237963947,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487900
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>BTW, I think nobody ever said it but I assume that this \"P\" thing takes a functor to left Kan extension?</p>",
        "id": 237963948,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1620487904
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes.</p>",
        "id": 237963954,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487917
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(I'd been talking to <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275899\">@Christian Williams</span> about this stuff beforehand, so I can read his mind on this.)</p>",
        "id": 237964028,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620487964
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right, that's how I use the notation too, but oddly it doesn't really matter that much in this situation, because the left adjoint in an adjunction is an equivalence if and only if the right half is.</p>",
        "id": 237964222,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1620488050
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So based on Morgan's feedback, let me try to sharpen <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275899\">@Christian Williams</span>'s question:</p>\n<p><strong>Question:</strong> given a functor F: C <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> D between small categories, is it true that P(F): P(C) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> P(D) is an equivalence iff  K(F): K(C) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span> K(D) is an equivalence, where K is the functor sending any small category to its Cauchy completion?</p>",
        "id": 237964354,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620488174
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Less verbosely and precisely: is it true that a functor between categories induces an equivalence between their presheaf categories iff it induces an equivalence between their Cauchy completions?</p>",
        "id": 237964411,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620488234
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We've just seen the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟹</mo><mtext>  </mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\implies</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.549em;vertical-align:-0.024em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⟹</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span></span></span> direction, but I have a feeling the converse is true too.</p>",
        "id": 237964429,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1620488264
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The other direction is trivial, because <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mi>K</mi><mo>≅</mo><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">PK \\cong P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> and 2-functors preserve equivalences.</p>",
        "id": 237964665,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1620488440
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe the other thing to say in this setting is that this can all be done more generally in enriched category theory. There, you again define the Cauchy completion <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K_V(C)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.07153em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> of a V-category C to be the completion of C under absolute V-colimits, and you again have, for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F: C \\to D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>, that the induced functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>P</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>:</mo><msub><mi>P</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>P</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>D</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P_V(F): P_V(C) \\to P_V(D)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.13889em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.13889em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.13889em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is an equivalence if and only if the induced functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>:</mo><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>K</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>D</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K_V(F): K_V(C) \\to K_V(D)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.07153em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.07153em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.32833099999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.07153em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is an equivalence.</p>\n<p>For example, taking V to be <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>≥</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>+</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">([0,\\infty],\\geq,+)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">([</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≥</span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, you conclude that a map of metric spaces induces an isomorphism of spaces of 1-Lipschitz functions if and only if it induces an isomorphism of Cauchy completions in the usual metric sense.</p>\n<p>Taking <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">V = Ab</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span></span></span></span>, you get the classical notion of Morita equivalence -- for example, modules over a ring <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> form an equivalent category to modules over the matrix ring <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>a</mi><msub><mi>t</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Mat_n(R)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>. </p>\n<p>And if you go oo-categorical and enrich in spectra, you start talking about surprising equivalences of derived categories -- there are a lot of them because for spectral enrichment, all finite limits and colimits are absolute.</p>",
        "id": 237980276,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1620503416
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Presumably there's a similar story for internal category theory, but I'm not familiar with it...</p>",
        "id": 237980329,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Campion",
        "timestamp": 1620503495
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Internal categories are basically set-like, so Cauchy completion again coincides with idempotent-completion.</p>",
        "id": 237992091,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1620516468
    }
]